WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.800
Hi, my name is Abigail Haddad and I got my first data science job offer seven years ago

00:00:05.800 --> 00:00:06.800
this week.

00:00:06.800 --> 00:00:11.520
I won't keep you in suspense, I did in fact take the job offer.

00:00:11.520 --> 00:00:13.960
So it's been a busy seven years.

00:00:13.960 --> 00:00:16.200
I've had five different jobs.

00:00:16.200 --> 00:00:21.280
I've read approximately 500 resumes of people applying to work at the various organizations

00:00:21.280 --> 00:00:22.840
I've been at.

00:00:22.840 --> 00:00:27.160
I've also applied to various talks like this and other ones where I did get to give them.

00:00:27.160 --> 00:00:32.680
And I've selected speakers for the data science DC group that I co-organize.

00:00:32.680 --> 00:00:35.599
And so throughout all of these, there's kind of a common thread and something I think about

00:00:35.599 --> 00:00:37.639
a lot, which is professional stories.

00:00:37.639 --> 00:00:42.080
So how do we communicate the kinds of things we're trying to communicate about ourselves

00:00:42.080 --> 00:00:46.439
and what we're bringing to the table for a possible future employer or in some other

00:00:46.439 --> 00:00:47.439
context?

00:00:47.439 --> 00:00:49.639
And how do we read other people's stories?

00:00:49.639 --> 00:00:51.160
Sort of what's the best way to do that?

00:00:51.160 --> 00:00:55.279
And like in the title, a surprising amount of the time for me in these experiences is

00:00:55.400 --> 00:00:57.400
GitHub.

00:00:57.400 --> 00:01:01.959
So here's the kind of story that I'm trying to communicate frequently about myself.

00:01:01.959 --> 00:01:05.639
And then I think you're probably trying to communicate about yourself as well and what

00:01:05.639 --> 00:01:06.639
you bring to the table.

00:01:06.639 --> 00:01:09.639
So that first part, obviously, look, it's coding skills.

00:01:09.639 --> 00:01:14.440
I'm data scientist, I write a lot of code, like way too much code.

00:01:14.440 --> 00:01:16.000
And that's part of what I do.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:18.040
But like you, it's not the only thing that I do.

00:01:18.040 --> 00:01:21.080
I also bring a particular problem solving approach.

00:01:21.080 --> 00:01:23.879
So when you come through with a problem, a set of requirements, there's a way that I

00:01:23.879 --> 00:01:24.879
approach that.

00:01:24.879 --> 00:01:28.760
There's also a set of technical practices and tools that I use, which of course has

00:01:28.760 --> 00:01:30.279
expanded over the years.

00:01:30.279 --> 00:01:32.160
I finally learned Docker a couple of weeks ago.

00:01:32.160 --> 00:01:34.800
That's been great, recommend.

00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:37.160
And also there's a set of communication skills I bring.

00:01:37.160 --> 00:01:39.199
So there's a way I write and a way I speak.

00:01:39.199 --> 00:01:43.239
And this is sort of, for me, this is a large part of the package that I want to communicate

00:01:43.239 --> 00:01:45.320
about myself.

00:01:45.320 --> 00:01:47.120
How do we do that?

00:01:47.120 --> 00:01:52.599
So first, a digression, junior resumes are really hard, okay?

00:01:52.599 --> 00:01:56.599
They're a really hard way of communicating the set of skills about yourself, I think

00:01:56.599 --> 00:01:59.000
even more than more senior resumes.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:00.720
And that's for a couple of reasons.

00:02:00.720 --> 00:02:04.080
First of all, that's because you're junior, you don't have a lot of job experiences in

00:02:04.080 --> 00:02:05.080
this field.

00:02:05.080 --> 00:02:07.599
So you don't have a lot of ways to say like, hey, I built this thing.

00:02:07.599 --> 00:02:09.320
Hey, here's how I approached this.

00:02:09.320 --> 00:02:14.039
The other thing is there are all of these data science and data analytics programs,

00:02:14.039 --> 00:02:16.520
and we don't know what they are, okay?

00:02:16.520 --> 00:02:21.080
So if you tell me you studied math undergrad or economics PhD, I broadly know what that

00:02:21.080 --> 00:02:22.080
means.

00:02:22.559 --> 00:02:26.479
If you tell me you studied data science, I actually don't.

00:02:26.479 --> 00:02:31.960
There isn't really a level of standardization, and even the same class across different programs

00:02:31.960 --> 00:02:34.720
can go into very different levels of depth.

00:02:34.720 --> 00:02:39.440
And so when I see that on a resume, it's hard for me to tell what that translates to, what

00:02:39.440 --> 00:02:42.479
you're bringing to the table, okay?

00:02:42.479 --> 00:02:44.320
So here's what we're going to be talking about today.

00:02:44.320 --> 00:02:48.759
I'm going to be going through why GitHub as opposed to the blog or the LinkedIn or however

00:02:48.759 --> 00:02:50.720
else you might communicate your skills.

00:02:50.720 --> 00:02:54.720
I'm going to talk about selecting projects that really show what you can do, that let

00:02:54.720 --> 00:02:59.520
you either build or show the kinds of skills that you want that future employer to know

00:02:59.520 --> 00:03:00.520
that you have.

00:03:00.520 --> 00:03:04.880
And I'm going to talk about some good development practices, both what I mean by good development

00:03:04.880 --> 00:03:10.839
practices and also how you can use them regardless of how big or small the repo that you're building

00:03:10.839 --> 00:03:11.839
is.

00:03:11.839 --> 00:03:13.839
First, why GitHub?

00:03:13.839 --> 00:03:16.720
Okay, so I'm on LinkedIn.

00:03:16.720 --> 00:03:18.839
I spent a lot of time on LinkedIn.

00:03:18.839 --> 00:03:22.240
I suggest you spend less time on LinkedIn than I spend on LinkedIn.

00:03:22.240 --> 00:03:28.080
I also have a blog, and I'm not going to tell you these things aren't useful, okay?

00:03:28.080 --> 00:03:33.199
But if you're looking for the lowest hanging fruit in terms of spending a hopefully small

00:03:33.199 --> 00:03:37.479
amount of time in a way that has the greatest returns, both to building your skills and

00:03:37.479 --> 00:03:41.000
showing off your skills, the answer is GitHub.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:44.880
And that gets back to these things that we're trying to communicate, our coding skills,

00:03:44.880 --> 00:03:49.360
our problem-solving approach, the kinds of tools we're using, and how we communicate, right?

00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:53.960
So you can write a post on LinkedIn, maybe it includes a graph or a finding of yours,

00:03:53.960 --> 00:03:59.639
and that's part of the story, but it's a very small part of that story, whereas you make

00:03:59.639 --> 00:04:02.539
a Git repo, and that's a much bigger part of it.

00:04:02.539 --> 00:04:04.759
So I'm seeing your actual code, right?

00:04:04.759 --> 00:04:10.039
I'm seeing that the way you got to that graph was some way where you wrote functions, your

00:04:10.039 --> 00:04:12.339
code was modular, you abstracted it out.

00:04:12.339 --> 00:04:16.100
But I can't tell that just from looking at the graph, I tell that from looking at the

00:04:16.100 --> 00:04:17.700
code, right?

00:04:17.700 --> 00:04:21.140
I'm also seeing how you communicate and how you approach a problem.

00:04:21.140 --> 00:04:22.980
So I'm looking at your readme, right?

00:04:22.980 --> 00:04:24.980
You should read me, we'll talk about that.

00:04:24.980 --> 00:04:29.299
So I'm seeing what problem you are trying to solve and how you came at it.

00:04:29.299 --> 00:04:33.179
And I'm seeing the broader set of tools that you're using, starting with using Git, right?

00:04:33.179 --> 00:04:36.779
Which is actually, like, not everybody knows how to use Git, and that's a great skill to

00:04:36.779 --> 00:04:38.059
bring to the table.

00:04:38.059 --> 00:04:41.700
So even if you're doing those other things, and again, I'm not going to tell you not to,

00:04:41.700 --> 00:04:46.899
I think GitHub should really be at the core of what you're doing for your portfolio.

00:04:46.899 --> 00:04:49.980
Additionally, it's industry standard, right?

00:04:49.980 --> 00:04:54.339
Using Git is something you are very likely to be doing at your next job.

00:04:54.339 --> 00:04:58.579
And if you're not using GitHub, you're probably going to be using some kind of internal Git

00:04:58.579 --> 00:05:00.500
server, GitLab, or something else.

00:05:00.500 --> 00:05:03.820
And so being ahead of that and showing you know how to use it, and that you're paying

00:05:03.820 --> 00:05:07.440
attention to broader industry norms is really useful.

00:05:07.440 --> 00:05:09.019
It's free, right?

00:05:09.019 --> 00:05:10.019
That's cool.

00:05:10.019 --> 00:05:14.059
I used to pay for a website, and I don't anymore, because I can get the functionality that I

00:05:14.059 --> 00:05:15.980
need from GitHub.

00:05:15.980 --> 00:05:20.100
And finally, and these two really go together, you're creating a lasting portfolio, which

00:05:20.100 --> 00:05:22.019
is actually likely to get looked at.

00:05:22.019 --> 00:05:25.899
You can post on LinkedIn now, people might look at it, they might look at it tomorrow.

00:05:25.899 --> 00:05:30.220
A year from now, when you're applying for a job, that possible future employer is very

00:05:30.220 --> 00:05:34.779
unlikely to be reading your year-old LinkedIn posts, whereas they really might be looking

00:05:34.779 --> 00:05:37.140
at your year-old repo.

00:05:37.540 --> 00:05:42.540
Okay, I did a very unscientific little question on this again, LinkedIn, and I asked people

00:05:42.540 --> 00:05:46.059
whether they looked at GitHub profiles when hiring for data roles.

00:05:46.059 --> 00:05:49.459
The majority said that they do look if it's listed, and some people said they actively

00:05:49.459 --> 00:05:50.839
search for it, right?

00:05:50.839 --> 00:05:52.899
And very few people said that they don't look.

00:05:52.899 --> 00:05:57.059
And so I can't promise you everybody will, but my sense is anything else we could have

00:05:57.059 --> 00:05:59.220
asked about, the numbers would have been lower.

00:05:59.220 --> 00:06:03.700
GitHub really is the thing where if you put a link to it on your resume, many people will

00:06:03.700 --> 00:06:05.959
go look at it.

00:06:05.959 --> 00:06:12.959
And finally, okay, so before I was a data scientist, I was a PhD student, okay?

00:06:12.959 --> 00:06:18.119
And I was scared, like for a much longer time, even after I finished my PhD, I had this sort

00:06:18.119 --> 00:06:22.440
of nightmare that somebody was going to ask to look at my code for my dissertation.

00:06:22.440 --> 00:06:25.519
And had they asked that, we would have had problems, okay?

00:06:25.519 --> 00:06:30.839
So the first problem was, I had so many, I was working in Stata, I had so many DO files,

00:06:30.839 --> 00:06:36.239
I couldn't actually have told you which created that final table or that final chart that

00:06:36.239 --> 00:06:37.679
was in my dissertation.

00:06:37.679 --> 00:06:38.679
So problem one.

00:06:38.679 --> 00:06:42.079
Problem two, the code was really bad.

00:06:42.079 --> 00:06:44.920
Like it was embarrassingly bad, it was very bad.

00:06:44.920 --> 00:06:47.959
And so I knew if somebody asked me, like I was going to go through this whole shame thing,

00:06:47.959 --> 00:06:49.839
it was going to be a mess, okay?

00:06:49.839 --> 00:06:51.839
I don't have that anymore, right?

00:06:51.839 --> 00:06:56.440
And I want you to not have that, because now when I code, I approach it from the perspective

00:06:56.440 --> 00:07:00.720
from the beginning that somebody is going to be looking at that code, right?

00:07:00.720 --> 00:07:04.100
I might look at it a year from now, I want it to be useful, somebody else might look

00:07:04.100 --> 00:07:05.100
at it.

00:07:05.100 --> 00:07:07.279
And that completely changes how I code.

00:07:07.279 --> 00:07:11.279
And also as much as possible, I put my stuff on GitHub from the beginning.

00:07:11.279 --> 00:07:15.279
And that way when somebody comes up to me and says, hey, which does happen periodically,

00:07:15.279 --> 00:07:16.359
can I see your code for this?

00:07:16.359 --> 00:07:21.119
I'm not stressing out, I'm not worrying about it, I send them to the repo, I call it a day.

00:07:21.119 --> 00:07:25.799
And that's been just incredibly powerful for me, and I want you to have that as well.

00:07:25.799 --> 00:07:26.799
Okay.

00:07:26.799 --> 00:07:29.239
So people ask me about how you pick a project.

00:07:29.239 --> 00:07:34.519
And the way I really think about it is, what are you trying to show that you can do, okay?

00:07:34.519 --> 00:07:38.760
So one of the things that I really appreciate about this field, and that's been really helpful

00:07:38.760 --> 00:07:43.600
for me career-wise, is that in most fields, most jobs you can have, the way you get the

00:07:43.600 --> 00:07:48.839
skill to either move up internally at your organization, or find a new job, is somebody

00:07:48.839 --> 00:07:50.799
has to tell you, hey, go out and do this, right?

00:07:50.799 --> 00:07:53.239
And you can certainly ask your boss, hey, can I do this?

00:07:53.239 --> 00:07:57.320
But you're really limited by what you're allowed to do at your current job.

00:07:57.399 --> 00:08:02.200
If you need experience organizing very large conferences, you can't do that on your weekends,

00:08:02.200 --> 00:08:03.200
right?

00:08:03.200 --> 00:08:04.200
You need to do it at your job.

00:08:04.200 --> 00:08:07.519
Whereas as a data scientist, and this has really helped me over the years, I don't need

00:08:07.519 --> 00:08:08.519
to wait.

00:08:08.519 --> 00:08:11.760
If there's a skill that I want, because I think it's going to be useful for me either

00:08:11.760 --> 00:08:16.079
moving up internally or at another organization, I can mostly just go get it.

00:08:16.079 --> 00:08:18.359
And that's been really amazing.

00:08:18.359 --> 00:08:21.799
So when you're choosing your project, I would say the first thing to really think about

00:08:21.799 --> 00:08:27.200
is what skill am I either trying to get, or just trying to show that I have?

00:08:27.200 --> 00:08:30.600
And I wouldn't underestimate the current set of skills.

00:08:30.600 --> 00:08:34.840
So for instance, if you are a junior in this field, and you know how to use Git, and your

00:08:34.840 --> 00:08:40.760
code isn't functions, and you write a readme file, that's actually really huge, right?

00:08:40.760 --> 00:08:45.479
And so if you're not on GitHub, I would really recommend spending a few hours, it does not

00:08:45.479 --> 00:08:49.580
need to be a part-time job, just showing that you can do those things, right?

00:08:49.580 --> 00:08:52.880
So it's both about the skill building, and it's just about showing the skills you have

00:08:52.880 --> 00:08:53.880
right now.

00:08:54.039 --> 00:08:57.760
And in terms of skill building, I would really, again, look at the kinds of jobs you might

00:08:57.760 --> 00:09:02.520
want to have, and figure out how to get those things, because you really, by and large,

00:09:02.520 --> 00:09:04.960
can get them on your own.

00:09:04.960 --> 00:09:05.960
Next, interests.

00:09:05.960 --> 00:09:06.960
Okay.

00:09:06.960 --> 00:09:11.520
So if you're trying to show, hey, I can get data from API, or I can do data viz, or really

00:09:11.520 --> 00:09:15.919
kind of anything, I can write functions, you can do that for any kind of data or any kind

00:09:15.919 --> 00:09:20.119
of interest that you have, and so why not pick something that you like?

00:09:20.119 --> 00:09:21.479
And finally, scope.

00:09:21.479 --> 00:09:22.479
So I mentioned this before.

00:09:22.479 --> 00:09:26.219
I really don't think GitHub should be your part-time job, right?

00:09:26.219 --> 00:09:29.640
You have jobs already, you have families, you have hobbies and friends, and all kinds

00:09:29.640 --> 00:09:32.619
of things that probably you would rather be doing.

00:09:32.619 --> 00:09:38.320
And so I would pick the smallest possible project you can do that either teaches or

00:09:38.320 --> 00:09:40.880
conveys what you're trying to convey.

00:09:40.880 --> 00:09:45.400
You can always build something out, but it's harder to shrink something once you've already

00:09:45.400 --> 00:09:46.400
started.

00:09:46.400 --> 00:09:49.000
And one of the things you're trying to show is that you can do something from start to

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:50.000
finish.

00:09:50.119 --> 00:09:55.719
So like, again, if what you're trying to show is functions, modular code, a readme file,

00:09:55.719 --> 00:10:00.520
if the only output of that is I made a table or I made a chart, that's fine.

00:10:00.520 --> 00:10:03.960
There's a lot you can show with a very small amount of code.

00:10:03.960 --> 00:10:06.679
And so scope it narrowly and then build if you want to.

00:10:06.679 --> 00:10:10.640
Finally, and I do want to mention this, put it on your resume.

00:10:10.640 --> 00:10:14.679
So personal projects are actually a really good thing to have on your resume.

00:10:14.679 --> 00:10:19.599
And just describing how you did it, here's the tools I used, again, linked to your repo,

00:10:19.599 --> 00:10:22.200
but that's a really good thing to see.

00:10:22.200 --> 00:10:25.520
Finally, good development practices.

00:10:25.520 --> 00:10:31.000
So I'm afraid like sometimes when people who are more senior say good development practices,

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:32.039
it can sound like this.

00:10:32.039 --> 00:10:35.080
It can sound like, here's a hoop we want you to jump through, right?

00:10:35.080 --> 00:10:36.080
Or gatekeeping.

00:10:36.080 --> 00:10:39.359
There's this thing that we spent the time and the pain learning.

00:10:39.359 --> 00:10:41.239
So we're going to make you do it too.

00:10:41.239 --> 00:10:42.960
That's not how I want to come across.

00:10:42.960 --> 00:10:47.479
And I think that's how most, that's not how most people in this field want to come across.

00:10:47.479 --> 00:10:51.159
When I'm talking about good development practices, I'm talking about three things.

00:10:51.159 --> 00:10:54.719
I'm talking about code that's easy to run, I'm talking about code that's easy to build

00:10:54.719 --> 00:10:59.440
on either for yourself or other people, I'm talking about code that's understandable.

00:10:59.440 --> 00:11:01.200
And that's really it, okay?

00:11:01.200 --> 00:11:05.580
And certainly what that means is different across different projects.

00:11:05.580 --> 00:11:09.520
If you're writing a package, that's going to mean a whole lot of things that it's not

00:11:09.520 --> 00:11:13.359
going to mean if you're writing something for yourself or even for your organization.

00:11:13.359 --> 00:11:17.020
But fundamentally, this is really all we're talking about, okay?

00:11:17.020 --> 00:11:18.619
So how do we do that?

00:11:18.619 --> 00:11:20.140
These are my sort of repo essentials.

00:11:20.140 --> 00:11:23.780
These are the things that I would recommend for any repo you're doing, no matter how big

00:11:23.780 --> 00:11:24.820
or how small.

00:11:24.820 --> 00:11:26.380
So your code is modular, right?

00:11:26.380 --> 00:11:27.659
It's in functions.

00:11:27.659 --> 00:11:29.619
Maybe it's in classes if you want, right?

00:11:29.619 --> 00:11:33.979
It's not just a block of text, but it's these little things that each do one thing.

00:11:33.979 --> 00:11:35.219
You're not repeating yourself.

00:11:35.219 --> 00:11:36.219
It's clean.

00:11:36.219 --> 00:11:38.460
Second, all your work is in code.

00:11:38.460 --> 00:11:42.299
There's not a part where like, here's the part where I pushed my data to Excel, I made

00:11:42.299 --> 00:11:44.219
some changes, I read it back in.

00:11:44.619 --> 00:11:47.460
Everything you're doing from start to finish is in the code.

00:11:47.460 --> 00:11:49.580
Next, it's organized.

00:11:49.580 --> 00:11:53.299
Maybe that means you have a subfolder for your results and a subfolder for your data.

00:11:53.299 --> 00:11:56.099
There's lots of different project structures out there.

00:11:56.099 --> 00:12:00.340
Maybe it means if your code is really big, there's multiple .py files and each of them

00:12:00.340 --> 00:12:03.059
kind of does something different and then you bring it all together.

00:12:03.059 --> 00:12:07.859
And so how this plays out is different for your different projects, but organization.

00:12:07.859 --> 00:12:08.859
It's documented.

00:12:08.859 --> 00:12:10.739
You have a readme file, right?

00:12:10.739 --> 00:12:15.340
Your readme file shows me what you did and why and kind of introduces all of it.

00:12:15.340 --> 00:12:19.380
I like docstrings because GPT writes me docstrings, right?

00:12:19.380 --> 00:12:20.380
Much faster.

00:12:20.380 --> 00:12:23.340
I don't write them on my own, but nobody's expecting me to have docstrings.

00:12:23.340 --> 00:12:25.299
You know, it's kind of fun.

00:12:25.299 --> 00:12:26.820
And finally, it makes sense.

00:12:26.820 --> 00:12:28.500
And that's harder to sort of describe.

00:12:28.500 --> 00:12:34.659
That's not like one technical thing, but what I mean is I can understand why you built what

00:12:34.659 --> 00:12:37.700
you did for the problem you were trying to solve.

00:12:37.700 --> 00:12:41.419
And maybe you find out midway through, actually, this isn't how I should have solved it.

00:12:41.419 --> 00:12:45.099
And you can put that in your readme and say, here's what I would do better next time.

00:12:45.099 --> 00:12:47.099
But really, it makes sense.

00:12:47.099 --> 00:12:53.900
Okay, so when I was going through this, I went to my own GitHub profile and I realized

00:12:53.900 --> 00:12:58.219
that my pinned repos, which are generally going to be the first thing somebody sees

00:12:58.219 --> 00:13:01.900
looking at your profile, were not actually the repos that I wanted pinned.

00:13:01.900 --> 00:13:02.900
Okay?

00:13:02.900 --> 00:13:03.900
So this is what it looked like last week.

00:13:03.900 --> 00:13:05.780
It actually looks completely different now.

00:13:05.780 --> 00:13:07.500
That was a good lesson for me.

00:13:08.299 --> 00:13:12.020
So when I say people are going to look at your GitHub profile, I mean it.

00:13:12.020 --> 00:13:14.219
But generally, they're not going to look at everything.

00:13:14.219 --> 00:13:18.299
They're going to kind of breeze by, and you want to make it as easy as possible for them

00:13:18.299 --> 00:13:21.539
to read the story that you want them to read.

00:13:21.539 --> 00:13:26.539
And that means pinning the repos you want them to see and hiding the repos you don't

00:13:26.539 --> 00:13:28.059
want them to see.

00:13:28.059 --> 00:13:29.299
And that's not nefarious.

00:13:29.299 --> 00:13:33.219
But like, for instance, if there's a repo that's pinned because you worked on it six

00:13:33.260 --> 00:13:38.260
years ago for a class, and it's a repo you didn't really contribute to, you cloned it,

00:13:38.260 --> 00:13:42.580
whatever, you added a little stuff, it doesn't really tell your story, then that's not

00:13:42.580 --> 00:13:44.219
something you want pinned.

00:13:44.219 --> 00:13:48.979
What you want pinned, and it can be one repo or up to six, are the things that do the best

00:13:48.979 --> 00:13:53.700
job of communicating the skills that you're bringing to the table, because that's

00:13:53.700 --> 00:13:55.979
probably what people are going to click on.

00:13:55.979 --> 00:13:59.500
I didn't show this, but if you have recent commits, that's the other thing that's going

00:13:59.500 --> 00:14:01.299
to show up, but I'm less worried about that.

00:14:01.299 --> 00:14:04.900
Generally, your recent commits are going to be things you want somebody looking at,

00:14:04.900 --> 00:14:09.140
whereas the things that GitHub decides it wants to pin really may not be.

00:14:09.140 --> 00:14:13.219
And so you just want to give this a look and make sure that if GitHub is on your resume,

00:14:13.219 --> 00:14:16.539
that what people are going to see first is what you want them to see.

00:14:16.539 --> 00:14:18.219
And I tend to ramble a little on that one.

00:14:18.219 --> 00:14:22.299
So here's the two-point version, which is hide repos you don't want seen,

00:14:22.299 --> 00:14:25.020
pin repos you do want seen.

00:14:25.020 --> 00:14:27.700
Okay, so next steps.

00:14:27.700 --> 00:14:31.979
So, look, if you're not on GitHub, I really recommend signing up.

00:14:31.979 --> 00:14:34.940
And I think this can be kind of scary, but it really doesn't need to be.

00:14:34.940 --> 00:14:39.340
You enter your email, you press continue, you begin the adventure.

00:14:39.340 --> 00:14:45.460
Also, if you're already on GitHub, I recommend looking at your old repos and maybe

00:14:45.460 --> 00:14:50.739
upgrading a little bit, thinking about what story you're trying to tell about that code,

00:14:50.739 --> 00:14:54.219
about those communication skills, about everything you're bringing to the table,

00:14:54.219 --> 00:14:58.500
and really making sure this is a good representation of what you're doing.

00:14:58.500 --> 00:15:02.340
And again, we're talking about coding skills, we're talking problem-solving approach,

00:15:02.340 --> 00:15:05.820
we're talking about the tools you're using, and we're talking about your communication.

00:15:05.820 --> 00:15:10.820
And all of those, you can tell a very good story with a repo.

00:15:10.820 --> 00:15:11.580
Thank you.

00:15:11.580 --> 00:15:16.020
I felt like I would be remiss if I did not include my GitHub profile on this.

00:15:16.020 --> 00:15:21.140
Also, LinkedIn, Substack, I've written a couple of posts about improving if you have

00:15:21.140 --> 00:15:26.020
Jupyter Notebook repositories, and also about sort of the larger issue of Git as a hiring

00:15:26.020 --> 00:15:28.099
practice relative to other things.

00:15:28.099 --> 00:15:29.859
And thank you for listening.

00:15:29.859 --> 00:15:36.859
This is...

00:15:36.859 --> 00:15:42.700
Okay.

00:15:42.700 --> 00:15:42.979
All right.

00:15:42.979 --> 00:15:47.380
We have a couple of questions while Alan sets up.

00:15:47.419 --> 00:15:52.460
So for some of us, we work on proprietary projects or pipelines, but how do you...

00:15:52.460 --> 00:15:57.059
Do you have any recommendations on how you can publicly show those skills that you've learned?

00:15:57.059 --> 00:15:57.979
Yeah, absolutely.

00:15:57.979 --> 00:16:00.419
So like as quickly as possible as you can.

00:16:00.419 --> 00:16:01.059
Okay.

00:16:01.059 --> 00:16:06.619
So if you have a set of skills already, then you want to find a way to sort of represent those

00:16:06.619 --> 00:16:08.260
skills in a new repo.

00:16:08.260 --> 00:16:12.179
So if you can't share your own stuff, you make a personal project, you think about what you're

00:16:12.179 --> 00:16:14.659
trying to communicate, and you just get it out there.

00:16:14.659 --> 00:16:17.179
Because I've been in that position too, working for the government.

00:16:17.179 --> 00:16:20.260
So like largely, I can't share the code that I write.

00:16:20.260 --> 00:16:24.900
But if you already have the skill, like that's where it's generally fairly simple.

00:16:24.900 --> 00:16:29.299
And there's some things you're not going to be able to build on your own and share.

00:16:29.299 --> 00:16:34.580
So if what your skill is, is like, I build robust pipelines for millions of users.

00:16:34.580 --> 00:16:36.140
That's not a GitHub project, right?

00:16:36.140 --> 00:16:37.179
Like you can't.

00:16:37.179 --> 00:16:41.140
But the more junior you are, the more likely it's going to be that there will be a quick

00:16:41.140 --> 00:16:46.979
personal project that showcases the kinds of skills you're trying to showcase.

00:16:47.619 --> 00:16:48.380
All right.

00:16:48.380 --> 00:16:52.419
How do you make time or prioritize putting personal code and projects on GitHub while

00:16:52.419 --> 00:16:53.619
coding for your job?

00:16:53.619 --> 00:16:55.419
Yeah, look, that's a great question.

00:16:55.419 --> 00:16:59.340
And one of the things I like about GitHub is that it doesn't need to be, like it's on

00:16:59.340 --> 00:17:01.059
your schedule, right?

00:17:01.059 --> 00:17:03.700
And so like job searching can take a lot of time.

00:17:03.700 --> 00:17:07.420
And like, I don't recommend waiting until you're job searching and then building out

00:17:07.420 --> 00:17:10.020
your GitHub profile because it does get really time consuming.

00:17:10.020 --> 00:17:11.219
So I sort of think about two things.

00:17:11.219 --> 00:17:16.060
It's doing it when you have time, and it's scoping it as narrowly as possible to show

00:17:16.099 --> 00:17:17.420
the skills you're trying to show.

00:17:19.780 --> 00:17:21.219
OK.

00:17:21.219 --> 00:17:25.500
What's an example of something you've improved on since showing your Ph.D.

00:17:25.500 --> 00:17:27.780
code and since you started coding publicly?

00:17:27.780 --> 00:17:28.939
Guys, it was so bad.

00:17:28.939 --> 00:17:30.500
My Ph.D. code was so bad.

00:17:30.500 --> 00:17:32.140
And no one's ever asked, which is great.

00:17:32.140 --> 00:17:36.140
And if they do, it's been so long that I feel like I don't, I can just say no at this

00:17:36.140 --> 00:17:43.060
point. But yeah, I mean, I definitely like this last seven years for me, but also for

00:17:43.099 --> 00:17:47.180
data science in general has brought us much closer to software development.

00:17:47.180 --> 00:17:50.140
And there are areas where like you don't need to be a software developer, really.

00:17:50.140 --> 00:17:55.699
But being able to write code that doesn't just run on your computer, right?

00:17:55.699 --> 00:17:59.859
Where I'm thinking about how to write this in a way that's more abstracted.

00:17:59.859 --> 00:18:06.500
So like in the last year, I started playing with CI-CD pipelines and unit tests in

00:18:06.500 --> 00:18:10.260
GitHub. So I have some repos where this is appropriate.

00:18:10.260 --> 00:18:16.260
So I write tests and every time I push my code and before I merge it in, it runs a

00:18:16.260 --> 00:18:20.540
series of tests in, I think it's like Python 3, Python 3.9, like different versions,

00:18:20.739 --> 00:18:22.099
Windows, Linux.

00:18:22.699 --> 00:18:24.819
And it runs my stuff to make sure that it didn't break.

00:18:25.060 --> 00:18:30.900
And I guess I don't know that for everything, but it's really nice figuring out

00:18:30.900 --> 00:18:34.819
whether your code broke like before you merge those changes in and not like, oops, I

00:18:34.819 --> 00:18:36.739
ran it and it broke. So I like that.

00:18:37.739 --> 00:18:41.219
All right, a question for one more, or time for one more.

00:18:41.660 --> 00:18:46.780
For humans on the hiring side, can you share your thoughts on how not to introduce bias

00:18:46.780 --> 00:18:48.459
due to the lack of a GitHub profile?

00:18:48.459 --> 00:18:50.180
Totally. So and this is funny.

00:18:50.180 --> 00:18:55.739
So since I put this, since I did this talk, I now change jobs and I'm not allowed to use

00:18:55.739 --> 00:18:56.819
GitHub in hiring.

00:18:56.819 --> 00:18:58.380
OK, so I don't because I'm not allowed.

00:18:58.579 --> 00:19:02.900
And I can still look at, if you list personal projects, I can still think about that.

00:19:03.540 --> 00:19:06.180
But yeah, look, I think this is a major issue.

00:19:06.180 --> 00:19:11.339
And I think we should never use, I think we should never penalize people for not having

00:19:11.339 --> 00:19:13.859
personal projects because there's all different ways you can learn things.

00:19:13.859 --> 00:19:15.099
So you can learn things at your job.

00:19:15.099 --> 00:19:16.459
You can learn things a whole range of ways.

00:19:16.699 --> 00:19:22.180
For me, when I'm able to use GitHub, it's more about bringing people in who otherwise I

00:19:22.180 --> 00:19:23.540
would not be able to bring in.

00:19:23.780 --> 00:19:28.420
Right. So if you haven't gotten that experience at your job because you weren't able to or

00:19:28.420 --> 00:19:32.699
for whatever reason, but you learned something then in some other context, then I think

00:19:32.699 --> 00:19:37.020
it's really important that you're still part of the hiring process, that we have a

00:19:37.020 --> 00:19:41.619
mechanism for saying, OK, you for whatever reason, you didn't get this at your job, but

00:19:41.619 --> 00:19:44.979
you taught yourself. And I think like I think being able to teach yourself is a really

00:19:44.979 --> 00:19:49.699
good skill. And I think no matter how you got a skill, we should respect that and use

00:19:49.699 --> 00:19:52.660
that because you're still bringing that to the table for your next job.

00:19:53.859 --> 00:19:55.979
All right, let's thank Abigail for her talk.

00:19:58.420 --> 00:19:59.420
Thank you.

